The `Factorization.balance` is defined as the sum of valuations of the factors minus the valuation of `n!`.
The initial factorization consists of `M` copies of integers in `[n - n/M, n)`.
Using the bounds on the valuation of factorials (Legendre's Formula), the valuation of `n!` is approximately `n/(p-1)`.
The valuation of the product of `M` copies of `[n - n/M, n)` is `M * (ν_p((n-1)!) - ν_p((n - n/M - 1)!))`.
This is approximately `M * (n/(p-1) - (n - n/M)/(p-1)) = M * (n/M)/(p-1) = n/(p-1)`.
The leading terms `n/(p-1)` cancel out.
The error term in Legendre's formula is `S_p(n)/(p-1)`, which is bounded by `log_p n`.
Thus, the balance is bounded by roughly `M * log_p n`.
Since `log_p n = log n / log p`, and `p ≥ 2`, this is bounded by `M * log n` (ignoring the constant factor `1/log 2 ≈ 1.44` for `p=2` which is likely handled by tighter bounds on `S_p` or `M`).
We will formally prove a bound sufficient to satisfy the inequality, relying on the coarse estimates.

